09131nam a22011775i 9780226619323DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019024387  a9780226619323  a(DE-B1597)545023  a(OCoLC)1140114012  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHD6279b.S64 2019 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a368.322300aSocial Security Programs and Retirement around the World :bWorking Longer /ced. by Kevin Milligan, Courtney C. Coile, David A. Wise. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (576 p.) :b320 figures, 19 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Conference Report00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Older Men’s Labor Force Participation in Belgium -- t2. The Labor Force Participation of Older Men in Canada -- t3. From Early Retirement to Staying in the Job: Trend Reversal in the Danish Labor Market -- t4. Explaining the Reversal in the Trend of Older Workers’ Employment Rates: The Case of France -- t5. Old- Age Labor Force Participation in Germany: What Explains the Trend Reversal among Older Men and the Steady Increase among Women? -- t6. Employment at Older Ages: Evidence from Italy -- t7. Labor Force Participation of the Elderly in Japan -- t8. Why Are People Working Longer in the Netherlands? -- t9. Trends in Labor Force Participation of Older Workers in Spain -- t10. The Recent Rise of Labor Force Participation of Older Workers in Sweden -- t11. Long- Run Trends in the Economic Activity of Older People in the United Kingdom -- t12. Working Longer in the United States: Trends and Explanations -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn developed countries, men’s labor force participation at older ages has increased in recent years, reversing a decades-long pattern of decline. Participation rates for older women have also been rising. What explains these patterns, and the differences in them across countries? The answers to these questions are pivotal as countries face fiscal and retirement security challenges posed by longer life-spans. This eighth phase of the International Social Security project, which compares the social security and retirement experiences of twelve developed countries, documents trends in participation and employment and explores reasons for the rising participation rates of older workers. The chapters use a common template for analysis, which facilitates comparison of results across countries. Using within-country natural experiments and cross-country comparisons, the researchers study the impact of improving health and education, changes in the occupation mix, the retirement incentives of social security programs, and the emergence of women in the workplace, on labor markets. The findings suggest that social security reforms and other factors such as the movement of women into the labor force have played an important role in labor force participation trends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAge and employmentxEconometric models. 0aAge and employmentzWestern countries. 0aHealth expectancyxEconometric models. 0aOlder peoplexEmploymentxEconometric models. 0aOlder peoplexHealth and hygienexEconometric models. 0aPost-retirement employmentxHealth aspectsvCross-cultural studies. 0aPost-retirement employmentxHealth aspectsxEconometric models. 0aPost-retirement employmentzWestern countries. 0aRetireesxEmploymentzWestern countries. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aeconomics of aging.  aemployment.  ahealth.  alabor supply.  aretirement.  asocial security.